@node not18 "GOODBYE CU AMIGA, GOODBYE"

GOODBYE @{B}CU AMIGA@{UB}, GOODBYE
-------------------------

@{I}FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE@{UI}

It is with great regret that I have to inform you that the October 1998 issue of
@{B}CU Amiga@{UB} will be the last ever published. @{B}CU Amiga Magazine@{UB} recently dipped into
a  state  of  unprofitability,  from  which  it  looked  unlikely to emerge. The
decision  to  close  the  magazine  was taken by @{B}EMAP@{UB} in light of the magazine's
overall  financial  performance  and  the lack of prospects for any immediate or
short term recovery.

It  is  ironic  that  @{B}CU  Amiga@{UB}  should  close as the world's best selling @{B}Amiga@{UB}
magazine,  but  recently  its  financial  returns  have  started to outweigh its
overheads. While it has been customary for costs to be cut in order to stave off
the  closure  of  magazines,  it was decided that @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} would be laid to rest
without  suffering  the  indignities  of  having  half its pages removed and the
remaineder  printed  on toilet paper in black and white. Neither will it be sold
off to another company to be published on a shoe string and run into the ground.

The @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} editorial team were obviously very sorry to hear the news and would
like  to  pass  on their sincere thanks to everyone who has helped make @{B}CU Amiga@{UB}
such a success and so much fun to work on over its many years of existence.

@{I}Tony Horgan@{UI}
Editor, @{B}CU Amiga Magazine@{UB}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{I}@{B}CU Amiga@{UB} Closure FAQ@{UI}

@{I}Q: Why is @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} closing?@{UI}
A:  Because  it is no longer making a profit and therefore cannot continue to be
published.

@{I}Q:  How can the best selling @{B}Amiga@{UB} magazine not make a profit when other smaller
magazines manage to do it?@{UI}
A:  Smaller  magazines  have  different  publishing set-ups, different costs and
different  distribution channels. Many are run at a slight loss or at break-even
by  dedicated  people  as  extended  hobbies.  @{B}CU  Amiga@{UB} is published by a major
magazine publishing company (@{B}EMAP@{UB}), and as a Publicly Limited Company (PLC) @{B}EMAP@{UB}
must  show its shareholders that it is making their money work, which means they
cannot  publish  magazines  that  make  a  loss.  @{B}EMAP@{UB} are a multi billion pound
international corporation; they have stuck with the @{B}Amiga@{UB} as long as they could.
Much smaller firms left years ago claiming the market was too small for them.

@{I}Q: Why are costs not cut in order to save the magazine?@{UI}
A:  That's  not  what @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} is about. We have always tried to make @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} a
watchword  for quality. The editorial staff and our publishers feel it is better
to leave on a high note than continually reduce the size of the magazine, remove
the  disks, reduce staff and investment in the title to keep it going regardless
of quality.

@{I}Q: Surely though something can be done?@{UI}
A:  We  could  reduce  the  magazine  to  a low quality pamphlet that was poorly
researched and written but then it wouldn't be worth the £4.50/£5.99 cover price.

@{I}Q: Why don't the staff all take a pay cut?@{UI}
A: Would you? And where would it end?

@{I}Q: Why have you lead us to believe the magazine would not close?@{UI}
A:  We  have always been honest and said that there would come a time (if things
did  not  pick  up) when the magazine would no longer be profitable. No-one knew
when  that  time  would be. We have been making money until very recently - this
has turned out to be one summer lull too much for us.

@{I}Q: Is this a plot to get @{B}Amiga@{UB} users to buy @{B}PC@{UB}s?@{UI}
A: No. @{B}CU Amiga@{UB}'s publisher has no @{B}PC@{UB} magazines anyway.

@{I}Q: Will @{B}"CU Amiga"@{UB} be turned into @{B}"CU PC"@{UB}?@{UI}
A: No.

@{I}Q: I have a subscription. What happens now?@{UI}
A: You will be refunded for the outstanding issues. Follow this link for details.

@{I}Q: Why isn't the magazine sold to a publisher who can make a profit from it?@{UI}
A:  Sacrifices  would have to be made by any pubilsher that would compromise the
magazine  so  that  it  would no longer be the @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} you currently know. @{B}EMAP@{UB}
have made the decision that they want to close @{B}CU@{UB} on a high rather than sell the
name on to let another publisher exploit.

@{I}Q: Will @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} return when the new Super @{B}Amiga@{UB} is released?@{UI}
A:  We  hope so, although we cannot make any promises on that one. That decision
will be in the hands of our (ex) publisher (@{B}EMAP@{UB}).

@{I}Q:  Can  I  take  this opportunity to thank the team for their dedication to the
magazine and the @{B}Amiga@{UB} community?@{UI}
A: Of course you can. Thank you.

@{I}Q: And what about us?@{UI}
A:  Well,  there's always @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} (as far as we know at this point anyway).
@{I}Nick@{UI}  and @{I}Ben@{UI} will look after you. We really are very sorry to have to leave you
like  this.  We  would  all  love to go on working on the magazine well into the
future  but  it's just not possible. One way or another we'll be around when the
Super  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  surfaces,  even though it most likely won't be a Class of 98 style
reunion of the whole team under the old banner.

@{I}Q: So is it time to pack the @{B}Amiga@{UB} away for good?@{UI}
A:  No! Keep on keeping on and we'll see you soon in happier times. We have been
a  point  of  contact  for the @{B}Amiga@{UB} community, but we are not the @{B}Amiga@{UB}, just a
magazine  about  it.  New products will go on being available, and your old ones
will work just as well without @{B}CU Amiga@{UB} in the newsagents.

@{I}Q: How do I contact you about anything?@{UI}
A:  Please  do not email any of our personal mail accounts with your comments or
queries.  We anticipate a lot of mail coming in over this, and we still have one
more  issue  to  produce - flooding our mailboxes will make this harder. You can
send us email on @{I}goodbye@cu-amiga.co.uk@{UI} - we will welcome your comments and will
be printing a selection of them in the last (October cover dated) issue.

The @{I}general@cu-amiga.co.uk@{UI} address and the @{I}goodbye@cu-amiga.co.uk@{UI} addresses will
remain  for  a  little  while  yet,  and  while we cannot promise answers in the
future,  someone  will  be  looking  in  on those accounts. Obviously our normal
section  related mail (Q&A, backchat) will not be dealt with any more. Please do
not mail us with technical queries in the future, there will be no-one to answer
them.
