@node not26 "SOFTSYNTH ANNOUNCES JFORTH RELEASED AS FREEWARE"

@{B}SOFTSYNTH@{UB} ANNOUNCES @{B}JFORTH@{UB} RELEASED AS FREEWARE
-----------------------------------------------

@{I}Press Release@{UI} - 21:00 Hrs. Monday 10th August 1998

May the @{B}Forth@{UB} be with you...Always !!!

Upgraded to @{B}OS3.1@{UB}

With  great  thanks  to  the  primary  authors, @{I}Mike Haas@{UI} and @{I}Phil Burk@{UI} who have
magnanimously  decided  to  release  this  product  (formerly priced at $179) as
freeware, the @{B}Amiga@{UB} now has another "arrow in it's quiver".

***** NOTE  -  Print  out  the  excellent  manual.  Not  only  does  it give you
      invaluable  information  on  the many tools provided, but there is also an
      excellent 3-stage tutorial *****

***** Join   the   @{B}JForth@{UB}   mailing   list  !!!  to  subscribe  send  e-mail  to
      @{I}MDaemon@ChaosSolutions.com@{UI}  with @{I}subscribe @{B}JForth@{UB}-list@{UI} as the only line in
      the body *****

@{I}What is it ?@{UI}

@{B}JForth@{UB}  is  a  programming language that allows you to interact with your @{B}Amiga@{UB}.
When  you  are  programming  in  @{B}JForth@{UB},  you are "inside" the language. You can
access  any data structure, test any routine, or use any development tool, right
from  the keyboard. This direct communication with the computer can improve your
productivity, giving you additional time to improve the quality of your software
products.

@{B}JForth@{UB}  is  based on the 1983 standard @{B}Forth@{UB} language. @{B}Forth@{UB} was first conceived
by  @{I}Charles  Moore@{UI}  when he wanted a new language for controlling telescopes. He
developed  a  language  based  on  a dictionary of words. This dictionary can be
extended  by writing new words based on the old ones. Since Mr. @{I}Moore@{UI}'s original
version,  @{B}Forth@{UB}  has  been  translated to almost every type of computer from the
biggest mainframes to the smallest microcomputers.

Since  a  minimal  @{B}Forth@{UB}  system  can  be implemented in just a few kilobytes of
memory,  it  is  often  used in very small embedded computer systems for process
control  and  robotics.  @{B}Forth@{UB}, however, is equally appropriate for larger, more
advanced, computers like the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. @{B}Forth@{UB} is a very flexible language and can be
adapted  to larger computers without losing the flavor of the original language.
@{B}JForth@{UB}  is  an  implementation  of @{B}Forth@{UB} designed specifically for the @{B}Commodore
Amiga@{UB}.  @{B}JForth@{UB}  uses a 32-bit stack and compiles directly to @{B}68000@{UB} machine code.
This makes @{B}JForth@{UB} faster than most @{B}Forth@{UB}s.

@{B}JForth@{UB}  also  provides  an  extensive  set  of  tools  for accessing the special
features  of  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}.  You  can  call  any @{B}Amiga@{UB} Library routine by name and
reference  any  @{B}Amiga@{UB} structure using constructs similar to @{B}'C'@{UB}. @{B}JForth@{UB} also has
some special toolboxes that support simple graphics, @{B}Intuition@{UB} menus, @{B}IFF@{UB} files,
and  other @{B}Amiga@{UB} features. These toolboxes can be used directly to simplify your
@{B}Amiga@{UB}  programming.  Source  code for all these toolboxes is provided so you can
customize  them if needed or study them as examples of @{B}Amiga@{UB} programming. @{B}JForth@{UB}
also  provides  over a dozen small sample programs for those, like me, who learn
best  by  example.  @{B}JForth@{UB}  also  allows you to do things that are unique in the
@{B}Forth@{UB} experience, the most dramatic being @{I}CLONE@{UI}. This exceptional utility allows
you  to  create  a  totally  independent,  standalone version of your program of
minimal size.

@{I}@{B}Amiga@{UB}  Library  Calls@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB}  provides a system for easily calling any @{B}Amiga@{UB}
Library  routine by name. It will figure out what @{B}68000@{UB} registers the parameters
go  into  and build the appropriate code. Thus you can simply pass parameters on
the  stack  in  the  order  described  in  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB} documentation. A number of
toolboxes  have  been written for supporting specific parts of the @{B}Amiga@{UB} Library
including @{B}EZMENUS@{UB}, Graphics, the Serial Device, @{B}ANSI@{UB} codes, and much more.

@{I}@{B}Amiga@{UB}  Structure  Support@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB}  provides the equivalent to all of the ".h"
include  files from @{B}'C'@{UB}. These ".j" files define all of the necessary structures
and  constants for passing information to the @{B}Amiga@{UB} Library routines. Structures
can  be  dumped  interactively  with  all  members  shown  by name and value for
debugging by using @{B}DST@{UB}. Upgraded to @{B}OS3.1@{UB} !

@{I}@{B}ARexx@{UB}  Support@{UI} - @{B}ARexx@{UB} is a language that helps various applications communicate
with  each  other. A spread sheet program, for example, could communicate with a
data base program. These tools help you write @{B}ARexx@{UB} compatible programs.

@{I}@{B}Assembler@{UB}@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB}  support  two  @{B}68000@{UB}  assemblers,  one  with @{B}Reverse Polish
Notation@{UB}  (@{B}RPN@{UB}) and one with @{B}Motorola@{UB} like syntax. The @{B}RPN@{UB} assembler can be used
to  create  macros but the @{B}Motorola@{UB} assembler is easier to read. There is also a
Disassembler.

@{I}Block Support and @{B}SCRED@{UB}@{UI} - For those who prefer the old fashioned BLOCK or SCREEN
environment, we provide LIST, LOAD and the standard line editor. We also provide
a WYSIWYG SCREEN editor called @{B}SCRED@{UB}. (We recommend the use of normal text files
with @{B}JForth@{UB}).

@{I}Clone@{UI}  -  @{I}Clone@{UI}  can be used to generate small, executable images of your @{B}JForth@{UB}
programs. @{I}Clone@{UI} will take a compiled @{B}JForth@{UB} program, extract out all of the code
and  data  needed to run it, and re-assemble a smaller version of it. All of the
@{B}JForth@{UB}  development  tools, the name fields and link fields and any other unused
words  are  left  behind.  The  final image size is comparable to images created
using a @{B}'C'@{UB} compiler and linker. Images can be saved with a symbol table for use
with  @{B}WACK@{UB}  or other debuggers (if needed). The @{B}JForth Source Level Debugger@{UB} can
also be used with @{I}Cloned@{UI} programs. Most programs will @{I}Clone@{UI} without modification
if they follow a few simple rules regarding run time initialization of variables
or arrays containing @{B}Forth@{UB} addresses.

@{I}Debugger@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB}  provides  a source level debugger that allows you to single
step  through your code. At every step you can see what is on the stack. You can
also  examine the return stack, dump memory, set breakpoints, control execution,
or even enter Forth commands.

@{I}Floating  Point@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB} support both the single precision Fast Floating Point
and  the  @{B}IEEE@{UB}  double precision. These words conform to the @{B}Forth Vendors Group
Standard@{UB}.

@{I}@{B}IFF@{UB}  Support@{UI} - @{B}JForth@{UB} provides general purpose tools for reading and writing @{B}IFF@{UB}
files.  It  also  provides  a toolbox specifically for @{B}ILBM@{UB} graphics files. This
allows you to use pictures, brushes, anims and animbrushes from a paint program,
or  other source, in your programs. @{B}JForth@{UB} also provides tools for animation and
presentation  such as, blit, wipe, fade in, fade out, etc. Powerful graphics and
animation programs can be created using these tools.

@{I}Local  Variables@{UI}  - Local variables can simplify the definition of complex words
by  eliminating  much  of  the stack manipulation. Local variables are fast self
fetching  variables  that  allow  reentrant  recursive code to be written. Using
regular VARIABLEs can make a word non reentrant.

@{I}Modules@{UI}  -  @{B}JForth@{UB}'s  precompiled modules provide a method for rapidly accessing
code  that  is  used  during  compilation.  This  includes  the  Assemblers  and
Disassembler,  and the @{B}Amiga@{UB} include files. These modules are dynamically linked
into  the  dictionary  when  needed. This way, they do not take up space in your
normal dictionary, yet are instantly available.

@{I}Multi-Standard@{UI}  - This system allows you to switch easily between @{B}JForth@{UB} and the
major  standards - FIG , '79 , and '83. This is handy for compiling code written
using other Forths. An @{B}ANSI@{UB} compatable module is being worked on.

@{I}@{B}ODE@{UB}@{UI}  -  @{B}ODE@{UB}  is an Object Oriented Development Environment similar in concept to
@{B}SmallTalk@{UB}.  It allows you to define classes of intelligent data structures, then
create  as  many  copies  of these data structures as needed. This technique can
simplify programming immensely by making it easier to write reusable code.

@{I}Profiler@{UI}  -  This  optimization tool monitors the operation of a program to find
out  where  it is spending its time. Most programs spend most of their time in a
small  portion  of  the code. By identifying this code, one can focus efforts at
optimization where they are most needed.

@{I}@{B}Textra@{UB}@{UI}  -  @{B}Textra@{UB}  is  a  powerful,  yet  easy  to use, multi-window text editor
designed  for programmers. It uses the mouse to select text and allows Cut, Copy
and Paste, operations between its windows. It also incorporates @{B}ARexx@{UB} hooks that
allows  you to use provided macros (.textra files) for text processing (or write
your own). @{B}Textra@{UB} can communicate with @{B}JForth@{UB} such that you can compile directly
from  the  editor.  If  an  error  is  encountered  while compiling, @{B}Textra@{UB} will
highlight the error so then you can fix it quickly.

@{I}Tutorials@{UI}  -  Beginner, intermediate and advanced guiding you through the basics
of the system.

@{I}Miscellaneous debugger tools@{UI} - Show hunks for analyzing @{B}Amiga@{UB} binary files

Graphics toolkits

Anims and animbrushes

...and so much more !!!

Don't  forget  to  print  out  the  excellent  manual. Not only does it give you
invaluable  information  on  the  many  tools  provided,  but  there  is also an
excellent 3-stage tutorial

