@node art02 "AMIWEST '98 SHOW REPORT FROM JEFFREY D. WEBSTER"

@{B}AMIWEST '98@{UB} SHOW REPORT FROM @{I}JEFFREY D. WEBSTER@{UI}
-----------------------------------------------

Needless to say, there were no overwhelming announcements. However, we did enjoy
some exciting guests. I'll start from the beginning.

Upon  arriving,  after  a  miserable  ordeal  with the airline, I was greeted by
@{I}Christopher  Aldi@{UI}  (@{B}ClassAct@{UB}, @{B}NewYork@{UB}). We were waiting for a ride to the hotel.
@{I}Bill Borsari@{UI} (@{B}UGN@{UB} Event Coordinator) picked us up. The madness began.

All of us were very high-strung, and excited about doing another show. All of us
except @{I}Robert Hamilton@{UI} (@{I}Lostman@{UI}) who was sleeping in the hotel room.

Sleeping?

On  Friday  morning  the  setup was underway. I tested my machine from the hotel
room,  and  then  assisted  @{I}Bill  Borsari@{UI},  @{I}Wayne  Hunt@{UI} (@{B}UGN@{UB}), and @{I}Darreck Lisle@{UI}
(@{B}Amiga,  Inc.@{UB})  in  setting  up  the  @{B}UGN@{UB} Booth. Not an easy task with 300 pound
Destination  monitors.  There were some difficulties, like the fact that @{I}Darreck@{UI}
had  to run 50 feet of phone cord out of the room and across a hall to get phone
service to the booth.

The  @{B}UGN@{UB}, headed by @{I}Wayne Hunt@{UI}, assisted by @{I}Darreck Lisle@{UI} and @{I}Bill Borsari@{UI} had a
nice  sized  booth  with  one Destination Monitor showing the @{B}UGN@{UB} Kiosk machine.
Which  was an @{B}A1200@{UB} running @{B}Scala@{UB}. It was professionally done, and with a lot of
help  from @{I}Casey Halverson@{UI}, it was even better. Connected with the @{B}UGN@{UB} Booth was
@{I}Lostman@{UI} with his @{B}Amiga@{UB} shirts, shorts, an sweaters.

Great  looking  clothes. We (the royal "We") shared a booth with @{I}Lostman@{UI}, though
we  had  no  product thanks to a complete lack of luck during the days preceding
the  show  (it's a sad story, perhaps another time). Instead, we were honored by
having  the @{B}UGN@{UB} use ChatBox for the IRC conferences. Another Destination monitor
showed  the  IRC  conferences.  @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} provided these monitors, by the way.
They did not have to. And it was greatly appreciated. Good job @{I}Darreck@{UI}.

Again,  I  have  to  give  a  hats-off to @{I}Bill Borsari@{UI}. He dedicates his time to
making  these  shows go off as smoothly as possible for the @{B}UGN@{UB}. He has aided in
keeping us well informed, and giving us a "@{B}WebCam@{UB}'s" view of the whole event. He
is  an  asset  to  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  community.  Come to IRC channel @{B}#Amiga@{UB} on servers
@{B}linux.us.amiganet.org@{UB},  or  @{B}whiterose.us.amiganet.org@{UB} and look for @{I}Bill@{UI} to thank
him for a great year of service. His IRC nickname is @{I}"tekmage"@{UI}.

On with the show.

To  the  immediate right of our booth was @{B}Nova Design@{UB}. @{I}Kermit Woodall@{UI} showed off
the  latest capabilities of @{B}ImageFX@{UB} with the help and expertise of @{I}Corinna Cohn@{UI}.
She  has  amazing skills with @{B}ImageFX@{UB}, and knows it like the back of her hand. I
bought  another  copy  of  @{B}Aladdin  4D@{UB}, as well as @{B}Catalyzer Volumes I@{UB} & @{B}II@{UB}. Big
Spender, eh?

@{UI}Chris  Aldi@{UI} showed off his line of products from @{B}Finale Developments@{UB}. As well as
@{B}"Digital Quill"@{UB} by @{I}Timothy Ashton@{UI}. Luck was not with @{I}Chris@{UI} for this show, as his
@{B}A3000@{UB}  went  on the blink. However, he did a great job in spite of it. He's been
dedicated to the @{B}Amiga@{UB} since the beginning.

@{UI}Harv  Laser@{UI}  was  right  next to @{B}Finale Developments@{UB}. Was he wearing the coveted
crown  of  the mighty "User Representative"? No, he was humbly dressed, greeting
people  as they passed, and enjoying lots of talk and stories. Of course, he was
also promoting @{B}AmigaZone@{UB}.

From  the  retail  standpoint we had @{B}Lively Computers@{UB}, and @{B}VisionSoft@{UB}. They were
far  too busy for me to even get a look at what they had for any length of time.
Both  companies  had great representatives that were friendly, and loved to talk
shop. What a great place to be.

One  of  the  most  interesting  conversations I had was with @{I}Bob Scharp@{UI}. A very
modest  individual  with an extremely kind wife. He has reason to brag, however,
they've  done  a  great  job  with the St. Louis show over the years. And I look
forward  to  exhibiting  there  next year. At his display were the nicest coffee
mugs  an @{B}Amiga@{UB}n could ever see. They had a black checkmark on one side and a big
black  circle  on the other side. Gee, sounds great, doesn't it? Well, pour some
hot  liquid  in  there  -- I suggest coffee, myself -- and the checkmark becomes
colored,  and  the large black circle becomes a smiling face. @{I}Bob@{UI} told me, @{I}"This
side  shows  a  black  check  mark because the @{B}Amiga@{UB} died, and this side shows a
black  circle because the @{B}Amiga@{UB} died. Put a hot liquid in the cup, and the check
mark  becomes  colorful, and the circle becomes a smiling face because the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
is alive again."@{UI} Cheers, @{I}Bob@{UI}! It was great meeting you.

One  person  that is always a joy to listen to because he is a virtual knowledge
bank  is  @{I}Holger Kruse@{UI}. He knows his stuff, and if you don't have @{B}Miami@{UB}, GET IT!
He  has worked tirelessly to give us easy internet access, and he's done it with
the  greatest modesty. And his intentions are unbelievable. Did he do it for the
money?  Did he do it for the recognition? Why did he work so hard for so little?
($30  a  copy is REAL cheap for a professional package like @{B}Miami@{UB}) He did it for
the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}, and it's users. At first we all questioned his intentions. Like, was
he trying to take over what @{B}AmiTCP@{UB} had given us?

Certainly,  but  without malice. He did it because the @{B}Amiga@{UB} community needed an
easy  way  to get on the internet. And, for those of you that criticize @{B}Miami@{UB} --
because  @{B}WinSock@{UB} is "free" -- don't knock it until you try it. @{B}WinSock@{UB} is "FREE"
for a reason. That is about all it is worth. @{B}Miami@{UB} is far more complete a TCP/IP
stack than @{B}WinSock@{UB}. Enjoy what you have. Thank you @{I}Holger@{UI}.

Now,  there  were some things I just had to see. I wanted to see @{I}Carl Sassenrath@{UI}
seminar  on  @{B}REBOL@{UB}  (sounds  like  "rebel").  This man has an excellent sense of
humor,  and he's very down to earth. @{B}REBOL@{UB} sounds like a very exciting language.
I can't wait to implement a @{B}REBOL@{UB} interface in some of our projects.

He  described,  in  great detail, how @{B}REBOL@{UB} really works, and what it's meant to
do.  He is so surprisingly Pro-@{B}Amiga@{UB}. Dedicated to his creation, I suppose. @{I}Carl@{UI}
also  spoke  at  the  banquet dinner, where he showed slides from the very early
days  of  @{B}Amiga@{UB}.  Included  in  the  slides  were  pictures  of  the  early  @{B}MOS@{UB}
implementations  of  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  Chipset.  He  had interesting stories about the
trials  of  getting the @{B}Amiga@{UB} to work. He shared many funny stories about events
that took place at @{B}Amiga@{UB}. @{I}RJ Mical@{UI} blowing up fish in the microwave?

Human society, anyone? ;)

Of  course,  the event we had all been waiting for. Hearing @{I}Jeff Schindler@{UI} speak
about  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}.  Oops.  Something came up, so @{I}Jeff@{UI} was unable to attend (I'll
elaborate later). Well, at least now we have Dr. @{I}Allan Havemose@{UI}.

Oops. You know the story. Big disappointment. But they more than made up for it.
Frankly,  everyone was pleasantly surprised by a man that very few know anything
about  --  besides  his  name.  @{I}Bill  McEwen@{UI}  was  an outstanding speaker, great
motivator, and despite his lack of techno-knowledge, an expert in this field. He
should  be  trusted  as  a  marketing director. He spoke very well, very clearly
outlining the intentions and the road map for the @{B}Amiga@{UB}.

Many  questions  were answered, without the usual thousand more that result from
the answers. He covered his speech with good humor, and professionalism.

His  speech  was long, but by no means unbearable (aside from there being no air
conditioner  in that room). He should be commended and thanked warmly for making
this  unexpected  trip  to  Sacramento  to  stand  in for @{I}Jeff Schindler@{UI} and Dr.
@{I}Havemose@{UI}. I was not at all disappointed, and left with even more confidence than
before.

@{B}S.A.C.C.@{UB} did a good job, this was their first show. There were some hitches here
and  there,  but  nothing insurmountable. And they worked hard to make it right,
and extremely upset and disappointed when they couldn't.

Despite  the sometimes flaring egos and tempers, we thank you @{B}S.A.C.C.@{UB} for bring
a  show  to  the western half of the states! Special thanks should go to @{I}Michael
Salcedo@{UI},  @{I}John  Zacharias@{UI},  and @{I}Alan Crandall@{UI}. Thank you for your understanding,
patience, and help.

I'll  be  working  with  @{I}Bill  Borsari@{UI}  and @{I}Casey Halverson@{UI} on some exciting new
projects  for  the @{B}MAE@{UB} (Ohio) show in October. We have some great things for you
internet show watchers. Keep your eyes peeled for press releases and news as the
show gets closer.

