@node art03 "BILL MCEWEN REVEALS THE PLAN AMIGA INC FROM A MARKETING PERSPECTIVE"

@{I}BILL MCEWEN@{UI} REVEALS THE @{B}AMIGA INC@{UB} PLAN FROM A MARKETING PERSPECTIVE
-------------------------------------------------------------------

Although  my  first  @{B}AmiWest@{UB} report was well received, I know it was lacking the
most important information. What did @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} have to say? More specifically,
what happened to @{I}Schindler@{UI}, @{I}Havemose@{UI}, and @{I}McEwen@{UI}?

I'll start with @{I}Bill McEwen@{UI}.

I apologize for not posting this earlier, but I had to review the video tapes so
that I could hit upon the highlights so as to avoid a long and drawn out post.

@{I}Bill  McEwen@{UI} is definitely a professional in marketing. He understands the basic
principles,  and  has  a  great  deal  of  knowledge  beyond  those  basics from
experience. He knows things you simply cannot learn in school.

On Saturday evening, July 11th, at the Banquet speech, @{I}Bill McEwen@{UI} elaborated on
the  @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} plans from the marketing perspective. He had a clear outline of
the path they'd like to take. I will not cover the entire presentation, only the
new items.

The news that we had all been waiting for was the revelation of the now infamous
@{B}"MMC"@{UB}.  I  have  no  such  news,  because  Mr.  @{I}McEwen@{UI} had no such news. He did,
however, have the minimum acceptable specification for the @{B}"MMC"@{UB}.

First the market statistics that motivate decisions in @{B}Amiga@{UB} Marketing:

@{I}Desktop OS Market@{UI}
                   1997-1998        2000 (projected)
@{B}Windows 95@{UB}/@{B}98@{UB}        69.4          65.0
@{B}Windows NT@{UB}            9.2          26.2
@{B}DOS@{UB}/@{B}Windows 3.x@{UB}       7.7           0.3
@{B}MacOS@{UB}                 4.6           1.9
@{B}Linux@{UB}                 2.4           4.2
@{B}DOS@{UB} (no @{B}Windows@{UB})      2.3           0.3
@{B}UNIX@{UB}                  1.0           0.5
@{B}OS/2 Warp@{UB}             0.8           1.2
**Other               2.7           0.5

Other includes @{B}BeOS@{UB} and @{B}Amiga@{UB}

It  is  obvious  that  our  target  market  cannot  be the same target market as
@{B}Microsoft@{UB}'s.  And,  according  to @{I}Bill@{UI}, the @{B}Amiga@{UB} must do in 1999 what it did in
1985 -- it must hit the market with an attention getting *BANG* that makes folks
think, @{I}"WOW! I have got to get me one of these!"@{UI}

The new @{B}Amiga@{UB} must fall within these loose specification:
 * @{I}Video & Sound@{UI}
    - Real-time 3D rendering engine with 2D primitives
    - HDTV
       ~ Up to 1920x1080
    - RGB, PAL & NTSC encodings
    - Multiple simultaneous MPEG-II decoding
    - Hardware filtering scaling, color space conversions, de-interlacing
    - Dolby AC-3

 * @{I}Multimedia / RISC System@{UI}
    - Scalable through multiple multimedia processors (like the @{B}Classic Amiga@{UB})
    - 56k modem (minimum)
    - @{B}PCI@{UB} Controller
    - Rich development environment - @{B}C++@{UB}, @{B}Assembler@{UB}, debugger, linker, etc.
    - Native @{B}Java VM@{UB}

 * @{I}CHIP SPECIFICATIONS@{UI}
    - 400 million textured, bit-mapped pixels per second. With 24-bit per pixel,
      this corresponds to 1.2GB/s of output from the 3D engine.
    - Comparison: @{B}ECS Amiga@{UB} has ~8M/sec max access to chip memory
    - @{B}A4000@{UB}/@{B}A1200@{UB}  systems  have maximum access of ~32M/sec to chip memory (Chip
      memory is where graphics and audio data resides)
    - 4 simultaneous MPEG-II decoders

The path that @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB} would like to follow is:
[ Taken directly from the presentation slides ]

 * @{I}Gaming@{UI}
    - Imagination is the only limitation for this platform
    [ This  where  the  money  is, and really what the vast majority of computer
    users want from their computers ]

 * @{I}Internet@{UI}
    - Connected to people, entertainment & information
    [ Easy connection to internet. Complete integration ]

 * @{I}Digital Media and Broadcast@{UI}
    - Digitized Realism
    - Expression of the imagination

 * @{I}Electronic Paradigm Shift@{UI}
    - Digital appliances prolific
    - Consumer Electronics and Computers converging
    [ Other  companies  are  trying  this  now,  but  all  are  going  their own
      direction. @{B}Amiga@{UB} can close this gap. ]

 * @{I}@{B}Amiga@{UB} Virtues@{UI}:
    - @{B}Exec@{UB} - best micro kernel in 1985
    - STILL the best now
    - Fully Pre-emptive

 * @{I}For new systems we need@{UI}:
    - Memory protection
    - Virtual memory
    - Multi-processor
    - Real-time
    [ @{I}Bill@{UI} points out that these are the goals for the new system ]

 * @{I}Custom API's made the @{B}Amiga@{UB} small, fast and efficient@{UI}
    - Need @{B}OpenGL@{UB}
    - Need @{B}Java@{UB}
    - Need Internet
    - Need Convergence API's

 * @{I}I/O in Custom chips@{UI}
    - Need @{B}1394@{UB} and @{B}USB@{UB}
    - Need @{B}ADSL@{UB} or similar high-speed network connectivity

 * @{I}AutoConfig@{UI}
    - @{B}PC@{UB}'s have "plug and pray"
    [ Although it sounds like a joke, the @{B}Amiga@{UB}, despite it's lack of drivers is
      more truly plug and PLAY ]

 * @{I}Dynamically configurable localization@{UI}
    - STILL the only game in town
    [ @{I}Bill@{UI} commented that this is a very important issue to Dr. @{I}Havemose@{UI} ]

@{I}Other points of interest:@{UI}

@{I}McEwen@{UI} stresses that the new @{B}Amiga@{UB} has to stand out from the crowd. Pointing out
that  current  @{B}PC@{UB}  options are intimidating, not easy to use, expensive, and are
often  obsolete  shortly  after  their release. This causes a great burden on an
already weary @{B}PC@{UB} purchasing public. The goals they have set forth will lead to a
personal computer where "personal" again has meaning.

This  has always been a strong point of the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. @{I}McEwen@{UI} mentions he's not from
this  camp [@{B}Amiga@{UB}], but he sees a community. He stated in his presentation that,
@{I}"@{B}Gateway@{UB}  didn't  have  this  big plan for the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. What they thought they had
were  patents  and  trademarks,  they  didn't  know  that  all of you [the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
community]  came  with  it."@{UI} The room broke with laughter. Indeed, @{B}Gateway@{UB} could
not  have expected such a resounding response from what was thought to be a dead
platform.

I  believe  they see us now, and not as a burden, but an asset. So, for those of
you  that  have  any doubts about their sincerity, give them a chance. Hear them
out. I know you will be as surprised as I was by their dedication.

All   of  the  bulleted  text  above  was  taken  from  the  slides  during  the
presentation.  Mr. @{I}McEwen@{UI} promised the bulk of them will be posted on the @{B}Amiga,
Inc.@{UB} site.

---

Now, on to the "issues" that seemed to infuriate so many in the @{B}Amiga@{UB} community.

What  happened to @{I}Schindler@{UI}? Did his wife give birth to a bouncing baby boy? Did
Dr. @{I}Havemose@{UI} deliver their child?

Needless to say, these rumors were unfounded... and just plain silly. First, Dr.
@{I}Havemose@{UI}  is not a medical doctor. Second, if @{I}Jeff@{UI}'s wife is pregnant, it's news
to he and his wife.

What happened to Dr. @{I}Havemose@{UI} then?

I'll  answer  that  in  one  sentence: More contract negotiations required their
further  attention  which distracted them from less pressing issues, like shows.
I'd rather have them there working, than at a show playing.

So,  to  clarify,  @{I}Jeff  Schindler@{UI}  and  @{I}Allan  Havemose@{UI} were not able to attend
@{B}AmiWest@{UB} because they had @{B}Amiga@{UB} business to attend to.

----

Thank you for your attention.

Transcriptions of the speech will be posted as they are completed.

@{I}Jeffrey D. Webster@{UI}
@{B}Mirada Innovations@{UB} / @{B}JDW Developments@{UB}
VP, Software Development / Marketing
