@node art06 "AMIGA & CU AMIGA - THE WHOLE STORY!"

@{B}AMIGA@{UB} & @{B}CU AMIGA@{UB} - THE WHOLE STORY!
-----------------------------------

This is an article from @{I}Mikey Carrillo@{UI} regarding the closure of @{B}CU Amiga@{UB}.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Fellow @{B}Amiga@{UB}ns.

Foreword:  Before  you  read  this  I  would  like to state that the information
contained  within  this  posting  is  as  accurately  truthful as possible and I
consider my sources to be honest and true.

In  short,  unless  later  stated different the information that follows is 100%
accurate.

Whilst the news of the closure of @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB} has hit us all very badly, all is not
as it seems and the news is actually very positive.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{B}CU-AMIGA@{UB}.  Whilst @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB} was actually the biggest selling @{B}Amiga@{UB} magazine, (60%
market  share)  it  wasn't the most profitable. (more on that soon) Basically in
the  recent  months  @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB} dipped slightly below profitability twice and @{B}EMAP@{UB}
publishing  decided  to pull the plug rather than to try to see if it could turn
it's fortunes around.

Bear  in mind that @{B}Emap@{UB} is mainly a women's magazine publisher it only has three
computing titles, @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB}, @{B}Playstation@{UB} and an Internet magazine. It may be also
said  that  with  only three computing titles they are looking to get out of the
computing  market  altogether  and  that  @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB}  may  be  the  first  of  the
'casualties' - although this is mere speculation on my part.

The  @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB} staff, are now sadly without employment (no where in @{B}Emap@{UB} for them
to go.) I hope someone else picks them up - They are amigans through and through.

Also bear in mind that @{B}Emap@{UB} is in business like any other publisher and may have
decided that they have to show the shareholders that they were determined to not
waste any of their money on a floundering title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{B}AMIGA  FORMAT@{UB} the second biggest selling @{B}Amiga@{UB} title of the two with only 40% of
the  market.  Published  by  @{B}Future  Publishing@{UB}  whom  publish 16 other computer
magazines.  @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} is Trading in PROFIT!!! Of the 16 computing titles that
@{B}Future@{UB} publish @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} is well above Several of them in profitability.

The  Management of @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} have assured @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} that they have got the
go ahead for another year of publishing. They are also quite confident that they
will be able to extend this. Hopefully to see in the New @{B}Amiga@{UB} and beyond.

As  a  result  of  @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB}s  closure, there has been an increase of Advertising
revenue  at  @{B}Amiga  Format@{UB}  and  this  will lead to the INCREASE of pages in the
magazine. (From about 108 now, to 124 or 130 pages) These will be made up from a
mixture of extra advertising and extra features/articles.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

I  have  also  taken  the  liberty  this  afternoon of speaking to the key @{B}Amiga@{UB}
Players  in  the  UK  from developers, publishers and retailers here's what they
said. (Note it makes very positive reading):

 * @{B}Active  Technologies@{UB}:  @{I}"Yes,  we  are  continuing  on  the @{B}Amiga@{UB} and are also
   developing new software to be unveiled at @{B}Cologne'98@{UB}"@{UI}
 * @{B}Alive  Mediasoft@{UB}: @{I}"We are staying. @{B}Alive Mediasoft@{UB} is EXPANDING we are taking
   people  on and we will be the LAST People standing on the @{B}Amiga@{UB} if Necessary.
   We are committed to the @{B}Amiga@{UB} 100%"@{UI}
 * @{B}Blittersoft@{UB}: @{I}"Business as usual - we will carry on supporting the @{B}Amiga@{UB}"@{UI}
 * @{B}Chroma@{UB}: @{I}"Yes, we will continue supporting the @{B}Amiga@{UB} for the time being"@{UI}
 * @{B}Epic  Marketing@{UB}:  @{I}"We  are staying with the @{B}Amiga@{UB} Platform, We are increasing
   our Advertising in @{B}Amiga Format@{UB} and will be producing more advertising flyers"@{UI}
 * @{B}Eyetech@{UB}: @{I}"Absolutely continuing to support the @{B}Amiga@{UB} - No question."@{UI}
 * @{B}Fore-Matt  Home  computing@{UB}:  @{I}"We  will continue supporting the @{B}Amiga@{UB} and very
   much  so.  we  are increasing our advertising revenue on the @{B}Amiga@{UB} and we are
   committed to it the @{B}Amiga@{UB} 100%"@{UI}
 * @{B}Power  Computing@{UB}: @{I}"We will continue to support the @{B}Amiga@{UB}, it remains the most
   profitable platform in our product range making up 70% of our income. We have
   also recently increased our advertising budget as well"@{UI}
 * @{B}White  Knight  Technologies@{UB}:  @{I}"No  change  for  us we remain committed to the
   @{B}Amiga@{UB} Platform but we will be increasing our direct mailings to our customers
   and also increase our DTV business"@{UI}
 * @{B}Weird Science@{UB}: @{I}"Debating"@{UI} (but I think they will stay)
 * @{B}Wizard Developments@{UB}: @{I}"No change - business as usual"@{UI}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

There  you  have it, take this and publish it anywhere were you think it will be
useful.

Tell  people  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  is  not  dead,  all the people I have spoken were very
positive about the @{B}Amiga@{UB}'s future.

While  a  lot  of people may point their finger and say that @{I}"But yes they would
say  that wouldn't they"@{UI} let me say that I have gotten to know some of them over
the  years,  and  I  didn't tell all of them I was doing this article - they all
appeared  very  genuine  in  their  replies  - Remember most of these people are
@{B}Amiga@{UB}ns and they are going to stick with the @{B}Amiga@{UB} through thick and thin.

An  Excellent  Magazine  has  gone  but it's not the @{B}Amiga@{UB}'s Fault, After all if
@{B}Amiga  Format@{UB} (with less circulation can be profitable) then you have to look at
the way @{B}CU-Amiga@{UB} was being distributed.

Perhaps,  if  the  magazine was as easy to find in the shops as @{B}AF@{UB}, they may not
have had to go..

-- Regards,
@{I}Mikey C@{UI}

Member: @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB}.
